The potential application of DE-CDs as cell imaging reagents was explored by laser confocal imaging experiments using Hela cells as models. The ability of DE-CDs for monitoring of pH in vitro was investigated by incubating cells with DE-CDs stocks at different pH. As shown in Fig. 4
                        , the orange fluorescence in the cells gradually brightened as the pH gradually increased. In addition, the intracellular orange fluorescence was enhanced after the addition of H2S (Fig. 5
                        ). Therefore, DE-CDs have the potential to monitor pH fluctuations and H2S in vitro.

As an excellent biological model, the zebrafish (ZF) is commonly used to assess in vivo cellular imaging capabilities. The in vivo imaging potential of DE-CDs was assessed by feeding 5-day-old ZFs with DE-CDs at different pH. The fluorescence in ZFs increased continuously with increasing pH (Fig. 6
                        ). At the same time, after feeding H2S to ZFs that had been fed with pH 7.4 DE-CDs, the fluorescence in zebrafish was significantly enhanced (Fig. 7
                        ). All these results demonstrated that DE-CDs can monitor pH fluctuations and H2S levels in vivo and in vitro.
